Description

Mineral names from RRUFF, with various properties from RRUFF, also Wikipedia scraped properties and links, joined by name with RRUFF plain string names. URIs are mindat numbers where they were matched in wikipedia, also manually updated by looking up.

Table of Contents

  1. Classes
  2. Annotation Properties
  3. Named Individuals
  4. Namespaces
  5. Legend

Apatitec

URI https://w3id.org/gso/1.0/mineral/apatite
Description

"Apatite" is a field term for unidentified calcium phosphate members of the apatite group. Most "apatite" is fluorapatite, whereas hydroxylapatite is much less common and chlorapatite is very rare. "Apatite" crystals are short to long hexagonal prisms [0001], with {1010} and {1011} dominant; also thick tabular {0001}, frequently in the crystals of hydrothermal origin in pegmatites and veins, with {1010}, relatively large {0001}, and often also {1011} or low pyramids. Massive, coarse granular to compact. Globular or reniform at times with a sub-fibrous, scaly, or imperfectly columnar structure or as fibrous crusts; stalactitic; earthy; oolitic. May be rock-forming in beds of great extent; as nodular concretions in clays and shales; conglomeritic.
Super-classes gsmin:apatitegroupc
Sub-classes gsmin:fluorapatitec
gsmin:chlorapatitec
gsmin:hydroxylapatitec

Brittle Micac

URI https://w3id.org/gso/1.0/mineral/brittlemica
Description

a sub-class of micas that contain divalent interlayer cations. The chemical bonding of the divalent cations as well as the concomitant substitution of AL for Si changes the physical nature of the mica from elastic to brittle and hence the origin of the name.
Super-classes gsmin:micagroupc
Sub-classes gsmin:clintonitec
gsmin:kinoshitalitec
gsmin:bityitec
gsmin:ferrokinoshitalitec
gsmin:oxykinoshitalitec

Clay Mineralc

URI https://w3id.org/gso/1.0/mineral/claymineral
Description

Informal term for a group of hydrous phyllosilicates: smectite, illite, chlorite and kandite, also kaolinite, halloysite, montmorillonite or smectite. Clays are usually distinguished by geologists or pedologists from other fine-grained soils and sediments by their grain size and/or mineralogy, though geotechnical engineers distinguish them by plasticity. Silt has larger particle size than clays; geologists usually consider the division to occur at a particle size of 2 µm, sedimentologists often use 4–5 μm, and colloid chemists use 1 μm. Geotechnical engineers distinguish between silts and clays based on the plasticity properties of the soil, as measured by the soils' Atterberg limits. ISO 14688 grades clay particles as being smaller than 2 μm and silt particles as being larger. (based on https://www.mindat.org/min-49430.html)
Super-classes gsog:Mineral_Materialc
Sub-classes gsmin:smectitegroupc
gsmin:chloritegroupc
gsmin:illitec
gsmin:kaolinitesubgroupc

Feldsparc

URI https://w3id.org/gso/1.0/mineral/feldspar
Description

A group of silicate minerals. May contain (very minor amount of) OH groups, considered as defects (e.g., Yang et al., 2015).
Super-classes gsog:Mineral_Materialc

Garnetc

URI https://w3id.org/gso/1.0/mineral/garnetgroup
Description

a group of silicate minerals with the same structure. All species of garnets possess similar physical properties and crystal forms, but differ in chemical composition. The different species are pyrope, almandine, spessartine, grossular (varieties of which are hessonite or cinnamon-stone and tsavorite), uvarovite and andradite. The garnets make up two solid solution series: pyrope-almandine-spessartine and uvarovite-grossular-andradite.(https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Garnet)
Super-classes gsog:Mineral_Materialc

glass c

URI https://w3id.org/gso/1.0/mineral/glass
Description

An amorphous, homogeneous material with a random liquid-like structure generally formed due to rapid cooling. Glasses can be natural rocktypes (such as obsidian, lechatelierite or tektite) or artificial materials (e.g., in slags). Most natural and artificial glasses are predominantly composed of silica with variable amounts of impurities, especially alkalis. (https://www.mindat.org/min-26411.html)
Super-classes gsog:Mineraloid_Materialc
Sub-classes gsmin:pseudotachylitec
gsmin:tectitec
gsmin:volcanicglassc

Halloysitec

URI https://w3id.org/gso/1.0/mineral/halloysite

The name halloysite currently stands for the two grandfathered and distinct species Halloysite-7Å and Halloysite-10Å.

Illitec

URI https://w3id.org/gso/1.0/mineral/illite
Description

This clay-like series is essentially a K-deficient muscovite, but frequently contains randomly sequenced montmorillonite/beidellite layers.

Kaolinitec

URI https://w3id.org/gso/1.0/mineral/kaolinite
Super-classes gsmin:kaolinitesubgroupc
gsog:Mineral_Materialc

kaolinite subgroupc

URI https://w3id.org/gso/1.0/mineral/kaolinitesubgroup
Description

Dioctahedral, Al-rich members of the Kaolinite-Serpentine Group. Within this group kaolinite, dickite and nacrite are actually polytypes of a single species, but the names have been grandfathered by the IMA. Kandite (min-32202) is an acronym for Kaolinite-Nacrite-Dickite.

Super-classes gsog:Mineral_Materialc
gsmin:claymineralc
Sub-classes gsmin:nacritec
gsmin:dickitec
gsmin:kaolinitec
gsmin:halloysitec

Labradoritec

URI https://w3id.org/gso/1.0/mineral/labradorite
Description

A plagioclase feldspar with an albite : anorthite molar ratio ranging from 30 : 70 to 50 : 50. An intermediate member of the Albite-Anorthite Series.

Micac

URI https://w3id.org/gso/1.0/mineral/mica
Description

True mica (as opposed to brittle mica). appears to include Dioctahedral mica and Trioctahedral micas. Subclasses here are based on Fleischers True Mica Group

Mica groupc

URI https://w3id.org/gso/1.0/mineral/micagroup
Description

A group of sheet silicates that can be parted into flexible or brittle sheets. Includes the True Micas and the Brittle Micas. Also known as the "mica family."
Super-classes gsog:Mineral_Materialc
Sub-classes gsmin:brittlemicac
gsmin:micac

Super-classes gsog:Mineral_Materialc

Opal-AGc

URI https://w3id.org/gso/1.0/mineral/opalag
Description

mineraloid consisting of aggregated spheres of amorphous silica, with water filling the gaps in between. Precious Opal and Potch Opal consist of this kind of structure - the difference being in the regularity of the sizes of the spheres and packing. Opal that shows no play of colours is also composed of the same spherical clusters, but they are non-uniform in size and do not pack in an orderly manner thus cancel out any possible diffraction of the light (Jones et al, 1964; Sanders, 1964). This type of opal is termed collectively 'potch opal' and includes the massive varieties. Porous varieties of inorganic origin such as geyserite and materials composed of tests of micro-organisms such as diatomite and radiolarite are also recognized. The X-ray powder diffraction pattern is essentially identical for of all these types of opal regardless of their origin. (https://www.mindat.org/min-32187.html)
Super-classes gsog:Mineraloid_Materialc

Opal-AN c

URI https://w3id.org/gso/1.0/mineral/opalan
Description

amorphous opal with a glass-like structure (Graetsch, 1994). The 'A' in the name stands for amorphous; the subscript 'N' is to imply its structure is network-like similar to silica glass; however, it still contains about 3-8 percent water, both as molecular water and bound in silanole (SiOH) groups. This form of opal occurs as hyalite in volcanic and pegmatite environments where the silica deposits from the gas phase (Flörke et al, 1973) and forms globular and irregular crusts. Because of its homogeneous internal structure, it does not show opalescence and is transparent if pure. The refractive index varies slightly with water content and lies between 1.44 and 1.46 (Graetsch, 1994). (https://www.mindat.org/min-1959.html)
Super-classes gsog:Mineraloid_Materialc

Perthitec

URI https://w3id.org/gso/1.0/mineral/perthite
Description

An intergrowth of albite or oligoclase with a microcline host, occasionally also with a orthoclase host. The intergrowths or exsolution lamellae of the albite are visible as white lines coursing through the K feldspar groundmass.

Plagioclasec

URI https://w3id.org/gso/1.0/mineral/plagioclase
Description

A series between Albite and Anorthite. In petrology, the plagioclase series are defined based on their percentage of albite (Ab) to anorthite (An). Compositions of individual samples are usually written as An24Ab76 meaning in this case that it is 24% anorthite and 76% albite.

Super-classes gsmin:feldsparc
Sub-classes gsmin:albitec
gsmin:bytownitec
gsmin:anorthitec
gsmin:labradoritec
gsmin:andesinec
gsmin:oligoclasec

shungite c

URI https://w3id.org/gso/1.0/mineral/shungite
Description

Shungite is elementary noncrystalline carbon with a metastable structure incapable of graphitization. Trace amounts of fullerenes (0.0001 < 0.001%) have been reported from such rock (Mosin & Ignatov, 2013). Shungite has a biogenic origin. (https://www.mindat.org/min-11040.html)

Smectitec

URI https://w3id.org/gso/1.0/mineral/smectitegroup
Description

Smectite a group name for platy phyllosilicates of 2:1 layer and a layer charge of ~ -0.2 to -0.6 per formula unit. Generally for natural samples, the d(001) spacing is approximately 14.4-15.6 Å, although other spacing may occur depending on H2O retention and interlayer occupancy. The group is further divided into subgroups that are either trioctahedral (according to Bailey, 1980, this subgroup name is saponite) or dioctahedral (subgroup name of montmorillonite, according to Bailey, 1980), and these subgroups are further divided into mineral species. Prior to circa 1975, the smectite group was called the montmorillonite-saponite group
Super-classes gsmin:claymineralc
gsog:Mineral_Materialc
Sub-classes gsmin:nontronitec
gsmin:montmorillonitec
gsmin:saponitec
gsmin:beidellitec
